<paragraph blockId="98.[264,1323,284,833]" box="[312,1278,644,670]" pageId="98" pageNumber="99">Etymology: The specific epithet refers to the exceptionally short cerci of the male.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="98.[264,1323,284,833]" pageId="98" pageNumber="99">
Comments: 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Marshall &amp; Cui" authorityYear="2005" box="[408,741,684,709]" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Robustagramma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="98" pageNumber="99" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brevicauda">
<emphasis box="[408,741,684,709]" italics="true" pageId="98" pageNumber="99">Robustagramma brevicauda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs obviously from all of the other species of this group because the vein R 
<subScript attach="left" box="[632,662,736,753]" fontSize="7" pageId="98" pageNumber="99">2+3</subScript>
is less curved forward, and the cercus of the male is exceptionally short. Other characters of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Marshall &amp; Cui" authorityYear="2005" box="[735,1066,767,792]" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Robustagramma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="98" pageNumber="99" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brevicauda">
<emphasis box="[735,1066,767,792]" italics="true" pageId="98" pageNumber="99">Robustagramma brevicauda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
leave little doubt that the species is correctly placed in the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Cui and Marshall" authorityYear="2005" box="[694,856,807,832]" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Robustagramma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="98" pageNumber="99" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavistylum">
<emphasis box="[694,856,807,832]" italics="true" pageId="98" pageNumber="99">R. flavistylum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group.
</paragraph>
